snippet.textDisplay:
I wasn't a fan of Rise of Skywalker. Not because it retconned Last Jedi, just it didn't do anything for me.

Generally, it feels hollow to me, being a string of events that happen so quickly that I just became numb over it all. None of the emotional scenes gave me any reaction, though most of the film seemed to be characters just getting to the next point. No one wants to discuss what's going on, how they're feeling or the like.

I will say it managed to pull off the character's emotions subtly at times by not talking... though the emotions mainly seemed simple. And the dialogue that was there doesn't have anything clunky or odd, it's just nothing special is all.

Yes, the film is wrapping everything up and from a lore perspective it's fine. I'm not a fan of a lot of the decisions the film made, but any of these ideas on paper is fine to me.

It feels like frosting to me.

I enjoyed the Last Jedi for attempting to think on about its themes and where these characters could go. It has so many beautiful visuals and takes the characters, mainly Rey, Kylo, and Luke, on a fantastic ride of story telling. I'm not a fan of how he tosses the Lightsaber and a lot of the dialogue is off. While I don't hate the Kanto Byte sequence like most, it isn't related to the main point the film was making. That should be an episode in a TV show or whatever.

Last Jedi I could see easy ways of fixing it's issues. Rise of Skywalker, not so much. Yes, from a lore perspective it's fine, but from a narrative perspective it goes everywhere. It feels similar to the Clone Wars miniseries, however I actually enjoy that. That's partially because it's animated and the timing for all of the scenes is just beautiful, but Rise of Skywalker is attempting to have a three act structure and not to be a miniseries. Plus, I feel the Clone Wars miniseries attempted to elevate its characters, giving them more characterization and progressing their arcs that episode 1 and 2 did not. Say what you will about the Last Jedi, but it did try to put the characters on a new path than where it started. It did do that by resetting some arcs, but it did give them all character arcs.

There are too many macguffins on this quest, at least for a film, and the film doesn't bother to really use the quests to develop the characters. There's a lot of scenes which will have focus on the characters, but the characters don't wind up changing from it. In fact, any sorts of stakes or consequences in this film tend to get undone. C3P0, chewy, kylo, and other things.

Oh yeah, and Hux is the spy... and then is killed. Then the Knights of Ren are here. Then a million Star Destroyers.



Rey and Kylo are the only two who have any internal conflict in this, and even then, it's a very dry version of what we got in the last two films. Last Jedi developed their relationship a lot more than this film, and where it left off did carry on in this film. Though that makes Kylo's arc a bit rushed returning to the light side.

I was fine with the Han Solo scene, him being a memory or the like is reasonable. Though Kylo simply switching all of the way to the light in that one moment is a bit much. Oh nevermind, it's because Palpatine was every voice in his head. Nah, I'm sure that isn't as literal as it sounds. Whether Palpatine was mind controlling Kylo or not, the turn was still rather sharp.

Now, I wasn't a fan of Palpatine's inclusion or that he's Rey's Grandfather, though if they handled it well I wouldn't have cared. However, they spent no time to build that up or really delve into that idea, to the point I wonder why he is her Grandfather. Not just why he's related by why he's her Grandfather. If he's still alive after Return of the Jedi, why couldn't he be her father? Oddly, JJ decided to roll with Rey being partially correct that her parents were nobody. I'd be fine if she was wrong about that, which she kind of is, but I guess she is right in a literal sense.

Though, I kind of would prefer if she was just nobody, keeping in the idea that heroes can come from anywhere and we can form our own futures. Though this film is more about lore than themes. If you're a fan of Lore, great. If you're not, you might not get as much from this film

I found myself in the theater laying there feeling dead after 30 minutes in and never mustered any more enthusiasm for the film after that. When talking about it with friend I play up hating the film as that's more fun than being depressed about it. I don't hate it, really, but eh... It kind of feels like any other work by the same writer, which just makes me confused why people who hate his work would like this film.

I just don't get how Palpatin numbers his orders. In the sequels we have the first and now the last. Fine. But his most successful one was the one that came before them - Order 66.

Also I don't think TLJ was a waste or canceled or anything. Luke wasn't just missing in 7 - he had to recover and that movie gave us his recovery. Rey got some lessons and established a connection with Kylo. Kylo became the Supreme Leader. We've also learned about some other things. A Luke that you need to piece together a map in order to find him in your hour of need is one who will toss a lightsaber. 

This movie? I need to see it again before I can make a judgement. It was fun. It was also a mess. Rey's lightsaber was cool but I think burying the sabers could have meant that the war is finally over. But then she lights a new one so probably not. Oh, well...

As for her being a Skywalker - She could have been adopted by Leia (who sort of treated her that way) or posthumously married Ben (they did kiss before he died and he can appear as a force ghost and say the words). though Ben was Solo and Leia usually went by the name Organa. But anyway Skywalker isn't a typical family. Anakin had no father. Where did he get the name from? It might just be whoever the Force picks as the current "chosen one". And anyway the Palpatines did nothing for her (selling her may have saved her). And anyway people changed names before.
